ments, oligarchs, and Muslim groups are integrated into presidential coalitions by giving them the same status as parties and parliament. But while this inclusiveness has made Indonesia's presidential system extraordinarily durable, it has also caused democratic decline. In order to secure the stability of their coalitions, presidents must observe the vested interests of each member when making policy decisions. The Coalitions Presidents Make details the process through which presidents balance their own powers and interests with those of their partners, encouraging patronage-oriented collaboration and disincentivizing confrontation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aCoalition governmentszIndonesia2DLC. 0aCoalition governmentszIndonesia. 0aDemocracyzIndonesia2DLC. 0aDemocracyzIndonesia. 0aExecutive powerzIndonesia2DLC. 0aExecutive powerzIndonesia. 0aPresidentszIndonesia2DLC. 0aPresidentszIndonesia. 4aInternational Studies. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Comparative Politics.2bisacsh  anon-party players, informal political actors, oligarchs, armed forces, bureaucracy, local governments, Muslim.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311075183308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2023 Englishz978311131925408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2023z9783111318677oZDB-23-PLW40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501772665?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501772665423Coveruhttps://www